            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " in eastern Uganda, writes about why aid efforts have so often failed in the Global South: “By strictly fighting global poverty in a very remote way, i.e., by channeling all global antipoverty funding through the biggest, western-based global anti-poverty agencies, the challenge is twofold: a) these agencies can’t practically be present in every impoverished village across the global south all at once, and b) the little work that these agencies can do only happens in a few random villages, and is almost always guaranteed to be short-lived.”",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
