      },
      {
        "type": "html",
        "html": "<table align=\"center\"><tr><td align=\"center\"><div>\n  <!--[if mso]>\n  <v:rect xmlns:v=\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:vml\" xmlns:w=\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:word\" href=\"https://dailyposter.outpost.pub/public/donate/60818189ad12f332071054b8#/donate\" style=\"height:50px;v-text-anchor:middle;width:140px;\" stroke=\"f\" fillcolor=\"#156CEB\">\n    <w:anchorlock/>\n    <center>\n  <![endif]-->\n      <a href=\"https://dailyposter.outpost.pub/public/donate/60818189ad12f332071054b8#/donate\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"background-color:#2a89b9;color:#ffffff;display:block;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:18px;line-height:50px;height:50px;text-align:center;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:none;width:140px;border-radius:5px;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;\">Tip Jar &rarr;</a>\n  <!--[if mso]>\n    </center>\n  </v:rect>\n<![endif]-->\n</div></td></tr></table>"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "A Message From The Daily Poster:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "koenig-heading",
        "tag": "h3",
        "version": 1,
        "renderVersion": "4.0"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Friends:",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "It used to be that the halls of power were seen as places of grand gestures. In movies and TV shows, the politicians who roamed these halls were either bold do-gooders (",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Mr. Smith Goes To Washington",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The West Wing",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "), or cartoonishly corrupt villains (",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Three Days of the Condor, House of Cards).",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Now, however, many have realized the truth: the halls of power are just like any other workplace: places brimming with mindless bureaucracy, where workdays are filled with random memos and pointless staff meetings. The only difference is that in the world of politicians, what hangs in the balance isn’t how many space sprockets are manufactured or whether all the TPS reports have cover sheets, but instead the fate of policies that impact thousands or millions of people.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The drudgery of modern politics can generate satire, as demonstrated by shows like ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Veep",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Parks and Recreation",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ". But it can also be horrifically demoralizing, especially when the curtain is pulled back on the thoughtless number crunching and paper pushing that is so often used to ruin people’s lives.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Daily Poster",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "’s Andrew Perez did that this week by ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "uncovering the internal documents",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "__GHOST_URL__/the-pros-and-cons-of-taking-money-from-your-constituents/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " Republican officials used in North Dakota to plan cutting off pandemic unemployment benefits to thousands of their state’s citizens. To justify ending the federal benefits, government staff noted, “Employers and a large portion of the citizen base do not believe the programs should continue,” but then added as a caveat: “No official survey completed, so somewhat anecdotal.”",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Almost as an aside, the staff noted that the jobless aid they planned to axe “provides [a] safety net to almost all ND citizens.” But really, who cares about that when there is “somewhat anecdotal” evidence that folks don’t think those programs should continue?",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The situation could almost be the plot of a sitcom — if the consequences weren’t so tragically unfunny.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "html",
        "html": "<table align=\"center\"><tr><td align=\"center\"><div>\n  <!--[if mso]>\n  <v:rect xmlns:v=\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:vml\" xmlns:w=\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:word\" href=\"https://dailyposter.outpost.pub/public/donate/60818189ad12f332071054b8#/donate\" style=\"height:50px;v-text-anchor:middle;width:140px;\" stroke=\"f\" fillcolor=\"#156CEB\">\n    <w:anchorlock/>\n    <center>\n  <![endif]-->\n      <a href=\"https://dailyposter.outpost.pub/public/donate/60818189ad12f332071054b8#/donate\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"background-color:#2a89b9;color:#ffffff;display:block;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:18px;line-height:50px;height:50px;text-align:center;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:none;width:140px;border-radius:5px;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;\">Tip Jar &rarr;</a>\n  <!--[if mso]>\n    </center>\n  </v:rect>\n<![endif]-->\n</div></td></tr></table>"
